In monodactyl intertidal oribatid mites there is a clear correlation between claw shape and used microhabitat (

). Strong selection acting on these claws has resulted in the loss of phylogenetic signal (

), which means claw shapes of closely related species are distinctly different if they inhabit different microhabitats. In the present study, the terrestrial species also show diverging claw shapes, but assigning shapes to a specific microhabitat or lifestyle is yet unfeasible. 

